      "body": "### Which @angular/* package(s) are relevant/releated to the feature request?\n\nanimations\n\n### Description\n\nCurrently the developer does not receive any information which can help him understand if a transition animation has been interrupted (by for example the user doing something)\r\n\r\nI'd imagine this could be achieved by the developer by tracking the time via the `start` and `done` callbacks and comparing the animation time to the expected time, but it does seem rather cumbersome and not something that the developer should do directly \r\n\r\nI'd imagine it could be handy to have some information indicating whether of not an animation has been interrupted/cancelled, so that the developer can see that and act accordingly if necessary\r\n\r\n\r\nRelates to https://github.com/angular/angular/issues/42946\n\n### Proposed solution\n\nI think that a `cancelled` field could be added to the [AnimationEvent](https://angular.io/api/animations/AnimationEvent) object so that in the `done` callback it can be easily checked\r\n\r\n(it would hover always be `false` in the `start` callback though, unless we'd want it to be `true` for disabled animations)\n\n### Alternatives considered\n\nThe AnimationEvent objects have a `totalTime` field, that shows the expected time the animation should take, that field could be updated to indicate how much time the animation actually took so that the developer could compare that with the expected time (I think that this can be more complex depending on the implementation of the callbacks and would also still require the developer to compare times, which from my point of view is sub-optimal)\r\n\r\n(or also another field could be added to the object as for example `completionTotalTime` which would indicate the total time that the animation actually took)",
