      "body": "### Which @angular/* package(s) are relevant/releated to the feature request?\n\nelements, router\n\n### Description\n\nWhen using `@angular/elements` in combination with `@angular/router`, there is a problem with the router: when the custom elements is removed/destroyed (`disconnectedCallback()` or `ngOnDestroy()`), the `Router` instance remains active and is still listening for route changes.\r\n\r\nYou *could* call `this.router.dispose()` in the `ngOnDestroy()` of the `AppComponent`, but then the router is no longer usable when the `AppComponent` custom element is created again.\n\n### Proposed solution\n\nI would propose a `reset()` method on the router that changes the internal state of the router back to when it was first created. So the same state as just before you call `this.router.initialNavigation()`.\n\n### Alternatives considered\n\nThis hack seems to work:\r\n\r\n```typescript\r\nngOnInit(): void {\r\n    const router = this.router as any;\r\n    router.navigated = false;\r\n    router.navigationId = 0;\r\n    router.lastSuccessfulId = -1;\r\n\r\n    this.router.initialNavigation();\r\n  }\r\n\r\n  ngOnDestroy(): void {\r\n    const router = this.router as any;\r\n    if (router.locationSubscription) {\r\n      router.locationSubscription.unsubscribe();\r\n      router.locationSubscription = undefined;\r\n    }\r\n  }\r\n\r\n```",
